ype":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the many places with this name in Buckinghamshire, Cornwall, Devon, Essex, Gloucestershire, Isle of Wight, Monmouthshire, Shropshire, Somerset, or the East Yorkshire. The placenames derive from Middle English <i>neue</i> ‘new’ + <i>port</i> ‘port, harbour’, also ‘market town’ (Old English <i>nīwe</i>, <i>port</i>).","History: The earliest known bearer of this name in North America was Christopher Newport (died 1617), an English mariner who served with Sir Francis Drake's Cádiz expedition of 1587. In 1592 he commanded a successful privateering expedition to the West Indies, taking 19 Spanish vessels. He married three times and had two daughters and two sons, one of whom, John, lived to acquire land in VA."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Newport was born in 1240, in Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales, her father, William Newport, was 27 and her mother, Mrs William Newport, was 28. She had at least 1 son with John Picton."},"et":{"1240–":"1240–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1213–Male":"1213–Surnud","1213–Female":"1213–Surnud","1213":"1213","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1240–":"1240–Kuollut","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1213–Male":"1213–Kuollut","1213–Female":"1213–Kuollut","1213":"1213","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1240–":"1240–Décédée","1240–Female":"1240–Décédée","1240–Male":"1240–Décédé","1270–Male":"1270–Décédé","1213–Male":"1213–Décédé","1213–Female":"1213–Décédée","1213":"1213","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Maud Newport est née en 1240, à Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Galles, son père, William Newport, avait 27 ans et sa mère, Mrs William Newport, avait 28 ans. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec John Picton."},"de":{"1240–":"1240–Verstorben","1240–Female":"1240–Verstorben","1240–Male":"1240–Verstorben","1270–Male":"1270–Verstorben","1213–Male":"1213–Verstorben","1213–Female":"1213–Verstorben","1213":"1213","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales","lifeSummary":"Als Maud Newport 1240 in Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales geboren wurde, war ihr Vater William Newport 27 und ihre Mutter Mrs William Newport 28. Sie hatte mit John Picton mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"1240–":"1240–Desede","1240–Female":"1240–Desede","1240–Male":"1240–Desede","1270–Male":"1270–Desede","1213–Male":"1213–Desede","1213–Female":"1213–Desede","1213"